We can represent the vertices of the decagon as complex numbers.  Let $z = \operatorname{cis} 36^\circ.$  Then the vertices of the decagon are
\[1, \, z, \, z^2, \, \dots, \, z^9.\][asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair moo (real t) {
  return (dir(36*t));
}

path foo = moo(0);
real t;

for (t = 1; t <= 9; ++t) {
  foo = foo--moo(t);
}

draw(foo--cycle);
draw((-1.2,0)--(3.2,0));
draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2));

label("$1$", moo(0), SE);
label("$z$", moo(1), NE);
label("$z^2$", moo(2), N);
label("$z^3$", moo(3), NW);
label("$z^4$", moo(4), SW);
label("$z^5$", moo(5), S);
label("$z^6$", moo(6), SE);
label("$z^7$", moo(7), NE);
label("$z^8$", moo(8), N);
label("$z^9$", moo(9), NW);
[/asy]

Since $P_1 = (1,0)$ and $P_6 = (3,0),$ $z^5 = 3.$  Then
\[(x_1 + y_1 i)(x_2 + y_2 i)(x_3 + y_3 i) \dotsm (x_{10} + y_{10} i) = 1 \cdot z \cdot z^2 \dotsm z^9 = z^{45} = (z^5)^9 = 3^9 = \boxed{19683}.\]

ground_truth:
Let $p_k$ denote the complex number corresponding to the point $P_k,$ for $1 \le k \le 10.$  Since the $P_k$ form a regular decagon centered at 2, the $p_k$ are the roots of
\[(z - 2)^{10} = 1.\]Hence,
\[(z - p_1)(z - p_2)(z - p_3) \dotsm (z - p_{10}) = (z - 2)^{10} - 1.\]By Vieta's formulas, $p_1 p_2 p_3 \dotsm p_{10} = 2^{10} - 1 = \boxed{1023}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

int i;
pair[] P;

for (i = 1; i <= 10; ++i) {
  P[i] = (2,0) + dir(180 - 36*(i - 1));
  draw(((2,0) + dir(180 - 36*(i - 1)))--((2,0) + dir(180 - 36*i)));
}

draw((-1,0)--(4,0));
draw((0,-1.5)--(0,1.5));

label("$P_1$", P[1], NW);
label("$P_2$", P[2], dir(180 - 36));
label("$P_3$", P[3], dir(180 - 2*36));
label("$P_4$", P[4], dir(180 - 3*36));
label("$P_5$", P[5], dir(180 - 4*36));
label("$P_6$", P[6], NE);
label("$P_7$", P[7], dir(180 - 6*36));
label("$P_8$", P[8], dir(180 - 7*36));
label("$P_9$", P[9], dir(180 - 8*36));
label("$P_{10}$", P[10], dir(180 - 9*36));

dot("$2$", (2,0), S);
[/asy]

